              <div class="region region-content">
    <div id="block-system-main" class="block block-system">

  
  
  
  <div>
    <div id="node-86663" class="node node-page clearfix" about="/about/community" typeof="foaf:Document">

  
      <span property="dc:title" content="Mathematics Outreach and Community Activities - overview" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>
  
      <div class="content campl-content-container">
      
      <div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="content:encoded"><h3>The Mathematics Faculty supports one of the largest departmental outreach programmes in the University, encompassing a wide range of activities, resources, and events for school students, teachers, families and the general public.</h3>
<h2>Working with schools </h2>
<p>The <a href="http://mmp.maths.org">Millennium Mathematics Project</a> (MMP) is an award-winning maths education and outreach initiative for ages 3 to 19 and the general public, involving staff in both the Faculties of Mathematics and Education at the University of Cambridge. The MMP's focus is on increasing mathematical understanding, confidence and enjoyment, and promoting creative and imaginative approaches to maths. <span style="line-height: 20.8px;">The Mathematics Faculty is also leading the DfE-funded <a href="https://undergroundmathematics.org">Underground Mathematics</a>.  In its pilot phase it was known as the Cambridge Mathematics Education Project</span> (CMEP).  The website has<span style="line-height: 20.8px;"> resources to support and enhance A-level and similar advanced post-16 mathematics education.  More information can be found on the Faculty pages <a href="https://www.maths.cam.ac.uk/underground-mathematics">here</a>.</span></p>
<p>Our support for schools includes: </p>
<ul><li>free online maths education resources for ages 3 to 19, developed and published by the MMP's very successful <a href="http://nrich.maths.org/" style="color: rgb(0, 114, 207); border-bottom-style: dotted; border-bottom-color: rgb(221, 191, 220); outline: none; font-family: verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 18px; text-align: start;">NRICH</a><span style="color: rgb(23, 23, 23); font-family: verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 18px; text-align: start;"> project. NRICH resources focus on problem-solving, and cover all stages of Early Years (ages 3-5), primary (ages 5 to 11) and secondary (ages 11 to 18) school education, through to support for students' transition from school to university. Detailed teacher support material is included.</span></li>
<li><span style="color: rgb(23, 23, 23); font-family: verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 18px; text-align: start;">The new <a href="https://undergroundmathematics.org/">Underground Mathematics</a> website provides free online rich resources to support the teaching of A-level (and equivalent post-16) mathematics. The resources support teachers in the classroom, and are designed to help students explore the connections that underpin mathematics.  </span></li>
<li><span style="color: rgb(23, 23, 23); font-family: verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 18px; text-align: start;">MMP project staff visit schools throughout the UK to run hands-on workshops for school students and professional development for teachers, and we also organise annual teacher professional development events held in Cambridge.</span></li>
<li><span style="color: rgb(23, 23, 23); font-family: verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 18px; text-align: start;">The MMP organises <a href="http://mmp.maths.org/events">events for schools</a>, such as maths enrichment days, held in Cambridge.</span></li>
<li><span style="color: rgb(23, 23, 23); font-family: verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 18px; text-align: start;">The MMP also hosts the East of England regional co-ordination for the <a href="http://www.furthermaths.org.uk/EE">Further Mathematics Support Programme</a>;</span></li>
<li><span style="color: rgb(23, 23, 23); font-family: verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 18px; text-align: start;">On a local level, the MMP co-ordinates STIMULUS, a student volunteer programme creating teaching placements in local Cambridge primary and secondary schools for volunteer Cambridge University students to help with maths, science and computing classes.</span></li>
</ul><p> </p>
<h2>University access and widening participation</h2>
<p>STEP Mathematics is an additional examination, taken at the end of Y13, which forms part of conditional offers to mathematics applicants by Cambridge and some other universities. We provide a number of free <a href="http://www.maths.cam.ac.uk/step-preparation-support-widening-participation">programmes to help potential university applicants</a> develop their advanced problem-solving skills and prepare for sitting STEP.</p>
<p>The Mathematics Faculty works with the <a href="http://www.undergraduate.study.cam.ac.uk/events-listing">Cambridge Admissions Office</a> to run study schools and access events for school students and prospective applicants, such as the <a href="http://www.undergraduate.study.cam.ac.uk/events/summer-schools">Sutton Trust Summer School</a>.</p>
<p> </p>
<h2>Events for the public</h2>
<p style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 18.79199981689453px;">The MMP organises a number of talks for the general public each year, especially during the annual Cambridge Science Festival in March. Details of public talks appear on the <a href="http://maths.org/events">MMP events page</a>.</p>
<p style="font-size: 13px; line-height: 18.79199981689453px;">We organise occasional Saturday morning <a href="/about/community/mathscircle/">Cambridge Maths Circle</a> events for families. The free events are open to ages 5 - 18 and accompanying parents and are an opportunity for children and young people to explore hands-on mathematical activities, with support from <span style="line-height: 18.792px;">volunteer Faculty of Mathematics students and staff</span>. </p>
<p>The <a href="http://cambridgesciencefestival.org/">Cambridge Science Festival</a> Maths Open Day takes place as part of the annual Cambridge Science Festival.</p>
<p> </p>
<h2>Online resources promoting the public understanding of mathematics</h2>
<p><a href="http://plus.maths.org/" style="color: rgb(0, 114, 207); border-bottom-style: dotted; border-bottom-color: rgb(221, 191, 220); outline: none; font-family: verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 18px;">Plus</a> is a free online <span style="color: rgb(23, 23, 23); font-family: verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 18px;">mathematics magazine aimed at the interested general reader. Plus articles, videos and podcasts cover a huge variety of topics, ranging from string theory or quantum information to climate change modelling and the applications of mathematics in fighting epidemic disease.</span></p>
<p><span style="color: rgb(23, 23, 23); font-family: verdana, arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 18px;">The <a href="http://understandinguncertainty.org/">Understanding Uncertainty</a> website, produced by David Spiegelhalter, Winton Professor for the Public Understanding of Risk, explores a range of topics related to chance, risk, uncertainty and probability.</span></p>
</div></div></div>    </div>
  
  
  
</div>
  </div>

